#### Issue details
`Container` overloads whole set of add/remove actor methods to define its specific singular child logic. But it has no override for `Group#removeActor(Actor, boolean)` which causes next bug: if child actor calls `remove()` on self, it triggers parent's `Group#removeActor(Actor, boolean)` and not `Group#removeActor(Actor)`, so `Container` will simply call super method (of `Group`) and keep reference to child actor.

Looks like regression bug, because javadoc of `Actor#remove()` also refers to `Group#removeActor(Actor)`, but actually calls only `Group#removeActor(Actor, boolean)`

#### Reproduction steps/code
``` java
Actor actor = new Actor();
Container container = new Container();
container.setActor(actor);
actor.remove();
assert(container.getActor() == null);
```

#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies
1.9.5

#### Please select the affected platforms
- [ ] Core

#### Issue details
When generating bitmap fonts in Hiero v5 using java rendering some glyphs are incorrectly positioned.
Notice for instance the "v" being positioned too far to the right.

![font_positioning](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7645564/23313711/18fa75d4-fabf-11e6-9612-cdaf2fccb02a.png)

I need the java rendering to create distance field fonts. I did notice that my old fonts, which work correctly and were generated with an older version of hiero (I believe 3.1) did not have any kerning details and the xoffset value would vary. In the newly generated (java rendered) fonts the xoffset is constant and it contains kerning details.

#### Reproduction steps/code

The fonts are generated with the default hiero settings when running the runnable jar from https://libgdx.badlogicgames.com/tools.html
The only setting I changed was the rendering setting. I have also had the same problem using my macbook so it seems that it is not a windows or environmental issue.

I have reproduced this problem using the following test application. Assets are attached below.

```
package com.mygdx.game;

import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.GL20;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.Texture;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.BitmapFont;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.SpriteBatch;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.glutils.ShaderProgram;

public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
	SpriteBatch batch;
	BitmapFont fontFreetype;
	BitmapFont fontJava;
	BitmapFont fontNative;
	
	@Override
	public void create () {
		batch = new SpriteBatch();
		fontFreetype = new BitmapFont(Gdx.files.internal("freetype.fnt"),Gdx.files.internal("freetype.png"),false,false);
		fontJava = new BitmapFont(Gdx.files.internal("java.fnt"),Gdx.files.internal("java.png"),false,false);
		fontNative = new BitmapFont(Gdx.files.internal("native.fnt"),Gdx.files.internal("native.png"),false,false);
	}

	@Override
	public void render () {
		Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0, 0, 0, 1);
		Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
		batch.begin();


		fontFreetype.draw(batch,"freetype",10,450);
		fontJava.draw(batch,"java",10,300);
		fontNative.draw(batch,"native",10,150);

		fontFreetype.draw(batch,"abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz",150,450);
		fontFreetype.draw(batch,"uvuvuv lvlvlv lululu",150,400);
		fontJava.draw(batch,"abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz",150,300);
		fontJava.draw(batch,"uvuvuv lvlvlv lululu",150,250);
		fontNative.draw(batch,"abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz",150,150);
		fontNative.draw(batch,"uvuvuv lvlvlv lululu",150,100);

		batch.end();
	}
	
	@Override
	public void dispose () {
		batch.dispose();
		fontFreetype.dispose();
		fontJava.dispose();
		fontNative.dispose();
	}
}
```

